ield of social philosophy and a person with a psychiatric disability, illustrates the importance of social interaction for developing and exercising agency. By overcoming mental illness stigma and by adopting certain epistemic and moral virtues, we can interact with people who have mental illness in ways that help enhance their agency and enable them to flourish.Humanizing Mental Illness demonstrates that we need to challenge our explicit and implicit biases and learn to interact with mental illness in more intentional, supportive, and inclusive ways.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aAgent (Philosophy). 0aMental illnessxPublic opinion. 0aMental illnessxSocial aspects. 0aMentally illxPublic opinion. 0aMentally illxSocial conditions. 0aSocial integration. 0aStigma (Social psychology). 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / People with Disabilities.2bisacsh  aPsychiatric disability.  aagency responsibility.  aepistemic virtues.  amental disorder.  amoral virtues.  asocial conditions.  asocialization.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311127221408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2021z978311127464540uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978022800734040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780228007340423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780228007340/original  a978-3-11-127221-4  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2021b2021  a978-3-11-127464-5  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2021b2021  aGBV-deGruyter-alles